Jan 24 2005	WORST HOTEL I HAVE EVER STAYED IN IN LONDON	I have just sent three nights at this hotel and the only good thing about it is the location. Perhaps I was just unfortunate but my visit was a catalogue of disasters. My room was unbearably hot and very dim (no lamps at all). I was moved to another room when the staff realised the heating was broken. The security lock in the second room did not work (essential for peace of mind when you are a woman travelling alone) so I went down to reception and was given a third room. The key would not open the door and it took three visits to reception before this was resolved. This room was in a poor and potentially dangerous state - the lamp behind my bed had come loose from its moorings and the socket by the dressing table was hanging off the wall. The heated towel rail was not wired in, with the bare wires left exposed. The hotel map showing location of fire exits was also missing. On the third day of my stay the key again didn't work and more trips up and down to reception were required. The door bracket at the top of my door had fallen off and kept jamming when I tried to close the door, as well as showering me with filth. I ordered from room service twice - the first time I asked for white bread and was given brown, the second time I ordered ham, tomato and lettuce sandwich with mustard - it arrived with no tomato, no lettuce, no mustard! Service in the bar was inattentive and my guest and I gave up waiting for dinner and went elsewhere. I travel a great deal and can honestly say that this is the worst London hotel I have stayed in - it bears no resemblance to the information given in its website.	
Sep 23 2004	4.5* Location. 2* Service.	I chose this hotel mainly due to location, apparent quality, and views. As for all my previous hotel bookings, I found no better price than octopustravel. Their site is easy to use and contains photos along with an abundance of information. So upon arrival, my girlfriend and I passed over the details of our booking to the concierge. After repeating the details numerous times, they couldn't find our reservation, but after 10 minutes we finally got the room key (what with the concierge simultaneously dealing with other guest's queries)...Once we got access to our room, we walked in to find a bed un-made, the tv on, and the bathroom with towels on the floor....I guess we were lucky that the current occupants of that room were out !!!! Needless to say, we returned back to reception and explained our situation, where the concierge apologised and gave us another room. This time, we were given a key for a twin room, despite booking a double room!! Yes, we returned back downstairs, and explained the 'new' situation. After a total of 35 minutes to check-in, we were now in a rush to be somewhere, and therefore asked if we could leave our bags behind the desk, and sort it out when we returned. We were told that we could go back up to the twin room and leave our bags there instead (Thanks!!). After explaining that we've had enough of the lift for one day, they decided to keep our bags behind reception. When we returned later in the evening, our key was ready, and our bags were in our new room. Thankfully, all was in order this time!!! This was my first experience of a 4* hotel room, and apart from the additional coffee-making facilities and immaculate bathroom, I found no real difference from a 3*. After finally settling in our room, we decided to go to the bar upstairs. Despite the somewhat hostile bar-staff and £4 charge for a bottle of beer, the bar area had great views of the skyline!! The next morning, we ordered room service breakfast, and despite some omissions from our order (such as toast), it was ok. However, from 9:30 to 10:45, we were disturbed by impetuous cleaners, wanting to clean our room. Ok, maybe we should've hung the 'Do Not Disturb' sign on the door, but after 6 times (later on with feeble excuses such as ''I wondered if you had enough coat hangers?''), we began to feel we were outstaying our welcome (despite the 12pm check out time!).I hope I'm not sounding too fastidious, but after spending a large chunk of my wages on the room itself, I personally expected to feel slightly more welcome....I don't know, maybe it's our age (we're both in our early 20’s)....or perhaps because we were staying there on leisure and not business??!?If it weren't for the location or views, I probably wouldn't stay at St.George's again. Though I would definitely browse elsewhere beforehand. Maybe the Bonnington? Hope this review is helpful. 3* room 4* bathroom 5* view 2* service 4* location	
Jul 25 2004	A Bit tired but Excellent for London	We Stayed in The st Georges Oxford Circus in July 2004. We were happy with the hotel, the decor in places was a little tired...but thats London for you. Some of the refurbishments were evident so we were overall happy with the hotel. The breakfast was boring after a ten day stay and a little expensive. We recieved clean linen and towels everyday and the room itself was kept very clean. The best features that will bring me back time and time again, are the views ( Spectacular) and the location. I would stay here again happily and recommend it as good value for money to friends and family. I must add however that the rooms are NOTHING like the internet pictures so dont set you heart on it!	
Jul 4 2004	not a 4 star!	My husband and I went to this hotel late June for 4 nights. We were shocked when we were brought to our first room. We were warned that London has a different standard for 4 star than North America but we were not prepared for this. There website said air conditioning , bathrobes, irons. Well this wasn't the case. The room was a sauna and when I called reception they advised me that it was central air. The knob fell off the radiator when I tried to adjust it, so they gave us a fan. The room was tiny, the carpet was stained , mirror was cracked, wood was warped and the furniture was getting threadbare. The washroom was a good size though. They moved us the next night to better room. And we found out that they are in the middle of remodelling some floors so depending on where your room is you could be disappointed .Our new room still had no Ironing board or safe. They only have a few safes and even though I asked every day for one they were always with other guests. They also do not supply wash cloths and I asked for 2 days, left notes for the maid. I was told repeatedly they would send some up but it wasn't until I went down to the front desk that I was informed that they discontinued that service. I have to say I was really amazed at how unfriendly the staff was and only one or 2 understood what good customer service was, the rest were rude and unpleasant. We weren't the only ones upset . I was present to hear a few people complain as they checked out regarding shower heads or the restaurant service. The location is great though and maybe if I had received one of the remodelled rooms I would have been happier but again service is everything and if you aren't made to feel welcome it isn't worth staying at.	
Feb 24 2004	Comfortable	The previous reviewer seems to be mentioning a different hotel, because as far as i am aware, this Saint Georges has nothing to do with Guernsey. I would like to correct the record--the Saint Georges nr Oxford Circus is a nice hotel.I'm American but living in Kent, and wanted a place to stay overnight in London on New Year's Eve (31 Dec 2003). My fiance found a reasonable rate (around 50 GBP or so) for a double--we got upgraded to an executive double. We had not tried the hotel before or even seen it, but it was a pleasant surprise.This hotel has an excellent location--about 3 blocks from Oxford Circus, but up Regent Street where it is quieter -- much less trafficked. Another positive aspect was the decor--our room was modern, spacious, with a view of rooftops. Nice furnishings/linens.The hotel restaurant is also excellent. It's on the 15th floor, very contemporary, and has nice views. We did not have breakfast following our stay, but have eaten there on another occasion, and the food was delicious. Service was also good.The drawbacks are that the lobby is small and there is not a lot of fancy furnishings there--a simple check-in desk (staffed with 1-2 people) and couch. However, this was fully satisfactory to our needs. I also found that the hallways seemed a bit stuffy/smoky and not refurbished as recently as the rooms. Finally, the hotel seems to be part office building as well, so the outside of the hotel is somewhat industrial-looking.I only mention these drawbacks because you usually cannot have everything perfect if you are looking for a reasonable price. However, the &quot;drawbacks&quot; were not problems for us at all and the quality of the rooms was very good value. Compared to the other reviews I have read of other London Hotels, this hotel rates highly to me.I have also been looking at scores of other local hotels as my relatives are coming in town but the Saint Georges rates (for when they are coming) are a little too high for their budget (esp with the US$ exchange rate!) and like many people they are trying to get as low a rate as possible, and willing to sacrifice some of the nicer amenities. OTherwise I would have them stay at the Saint Georges which is much nicer than some of the ones I have seen out there!	
